snippet.textDisplay:
am i just dumb cause i don't get the criticism of batman "looming" over the film...isn't that the point? Did the creators announce beforehand that they weren't going to have batman involved or something? I'm just confused how that's a sin because isn't that the whole purpose of the Joker? Batman is his nemesis so it makes sense for him to act as a foil or double to Joker in the movie. He's not actually a character, but a device to contrast against Joker. I don't see anything wrong with that - if anything, I thought it was incorporated quite well.

Also the part about "how do people know enough about this story to have an opinion that the poor person was shooting at the rich people for a reason that would rally them behind a killer?" - isn't that the point? That just because two rich people were found dead, people turn it into a "rich vs poor" movement because the wealth gap is that big in Gotham and people are that desparate. That it just takes an act like that, that may not even be purposeful or significant, for the public and the media to overblow it and turn it into something it's not to fit their agenda. I dunno, just seems pretty realistic considering all kinds of happenings in the world recently
idk I didn't think this movie was as great as everyone was saying - it is really well done for sure but it isn't actually that original. This video hits some sins right on the money, but other parts I'm not sure can really count as "sins"... For example, the movie is following an unreliable protagonist so I don't think it is particularly justified to criticise it based on real-world rules. I think some parts are supposed to be not believable and this adds to the effect as we don't know whether it is in Arthur's head or not which projects his struggles onto us. For example, in the movie cinema, the people appear too self-absorbed to notice a literal clown walking down the aisle. But we could also take it as Arthur's POV in that he sees everyone ignoring him, but perhaps they actually aren't - he just isn't registering that. Or perhaps the cinema is more empty than the shot actually shows, but Joker is seeing it full of all the rich people he hates and envies and is fantasising about being there and no one taking notice that he's snuck in. Maybe Charlie Chaplin isn't actually showing, and this isn't actually what the place looks like. Maybe joker is actually just in the doorway at the back, not halfway down the aisle. We don't actually know, because we know Joker makes up whole scenarios in his head of various believability. In other words, this movie has a lot of artistic shots that don't necessarily have to be taken at face value. In essence, that is a secondary theme of the movie - perceived reality vs actual reality. In my opinion, that's what made it a good film - I saw fake relationship a mile off and it was a bit of a cheap plot twist, but the fact that this makes us question everything afterwards adds to the impact of the film's portrayal of mental illness - it makes us as the audience feel the same uneasiness Arthur does. So I definitely think a lot of it is purposely made strangely 'convenient' because it makes us question everything and the fact that we really don't know what is 'real' or not. Or in fact, if any of it is real. For all we know, Arthur is projecting real life events onto himself and the whole movie is an exaggerated POV. But I think that's ultimately why a lot of people liked the vibe and 'feeling' of the movie. I know cinemasins most likely knows all this, but has chosen to take a more literal approach as they usually do. But I also don't think they should analyse this like the other movies they do. Just my opinion 🤷‍♀️

snippet.textDisplay: From a linguistic standpoint, Arthur's "spelling" mistakes make perfect sense. Since "half" is followed by "to" in this example, it's natural to want to flow speech together thus the devocalization of the ending v sound in "have"  to match the beginning t in "to," an unvoiced plosive. He's spelling it "half" due to him trying to find a word with the phonetic spelling of how "have" is pronounced in this instance, not because he doesn't know the verb "have." This speech error is called a malapropism and is prevalent throughout literature and media for comedic effect and otherwise portraying a character as uneducated/not fluent in a language.
snippet.textOriginal: From a linguistic standpoint, Arthur's "spelling" mistakes make perfect sense. Since "half" is followed by "to" in this example, it's natural to want to flow speech together thus the devocalization of the ending v sound in "have"  to match the beginning t in "to," an unvoiced plosive. He's spelling it "half" due to him trying to find a word with the phonetic spelling of how "have" is pronounced in this instance, not because he doesn't know the verb "have."
